04383nam a22005055i 9780804771146DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202009cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047711467 a10.1515/97808047711462doi  a(DE-B1597)564320  a(OCoLC)1178769854  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHD70.L29bB44 2009eb 7aBUS0410002bisacsh04a302.3/52221 aBehrens, Alfredo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCulture and Management in the Americas /cAlfredo Behrens. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tWho Should Read What in This Book -- tIntroduction: Countries of the Future, Forever? -- tPart One. Culture and the Americas -- tPart Two. Cultural Tributaries of the New World -- tPart Three. Cultures of the New World -- tPart Four. Cross -Cultural Management: The Toolbox -- tPart Five. Measuring the Impact of Culture on Management -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLatin Americans are culturally different from North Americans in ways that so far have been inaccurately portrayed in the management literature. In Culture and Management in the Americas, Alfredo Behrens argues that these differences merit a substantial overhaul of management theory and practice to make the best of the significantly untapped Latin American potential for creativity, innovation, and teamwork. This applies in organizations with North American ownership and management, whether they are based in the U.S. or Latin America. Behrens, a management consultant and academic who has studied, taught, and practiced in South and North America and Europe, explains why the use of traditional North American research methods to capture cultural traits in the multi-cultural workforce is inappropriate. This practice produces a false picture of the cultural attributes and capabilities of Latin American managers and key staff. And this, in turn, leads to serious shortcomings in the development of appropriate motivation and leadership strategies and of appraisal and control instruments. Rather than relying on standardized surveys for measuring cultural attributes to underpin and develop such strategies and tools, the author suggests that managers look to the arts-particularly literature and cinema-for a richer and more useful alternative. He illustrates his points by reference to literary icons such as Argentina's Martin Fierro, Brazil's Macunaima, and America's Captain Ahab. He uses a variety of case studies to demonstrate what we can learn from these iconographic characters and what we can expect of each other when we apply these lessons-whether we are leading, following, or working in self-directed teams. This readable and enjoyable book will be an invaluable, engaging, and practical tool for anyone charged with managing at any level in workforce that combines both North American and Latin American cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aManagementxSocial aspectsxLatin America. 0aManagementxSocial aspectszLatin America. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Management.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804771146zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804771146423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804771146.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles